div.p:
Therewith he gives the meal-bag into his hands while he himself went to fetch firing;
           but when he came back the youngling had done naught at the bread-making. Then asks
           Sigmund if the bread be ready --

Now Sigmund was so mighty a man that he might eat venom and have no hurt therefrom;
           but Sinfjotli might abide whatso venom came on the outside of him, but might neither eat
           nor drink thereof.

Brynhild answered, "Surely for many an ill-deed must I reward them; mind me not of my
           griefs against them! But thou, Sigurd, slewest the Worm, and rodest the fire through;
           yea, and for my sake, and not one of the sons of King Giuki."
